the chariot that evolved from the ancient vehicle of this name (see chariot) took on two main forms: 
*  a light, four-wheeled, horse-drawn carriage having a coach box and back seats only, popular in the early 19th century. 
*  a vehicle for conveying persons especially in state, such as a triumphal car or a coach of state. this stately but manoeuvrable horse carriage was used for ceremonial occasions or for pleasure. a chariotee was a light, covered, four-wheeled pleasure carriage with two seats. a post chariot was a carriage for traveling post. the term was used specifically for a kind of light four-wheeled carriage with a driver's seat in front. a vehicle such as a cart or wagon for transporting goods was also sometimes called a chariot.